
âœ… What is Hoisting in JavaScript?
Hoisting is JavaScript's default behavior of moving declarations to the top of the current scope (before code execution).

ğŸ” What gets hoisted?
Type	Declaration Hoisted?	Initialization Hoisted?
var	âœ… Yes	âŒ No
let / const	âœ… Yes (in TDZ)	âŒ No
function	âœ… Yes (fully)	âœ… Yes
arrow function	âŒ No (if assigned to var/let/const)	âŒ No

ğŸ§  Example 1 â€“ var hoisting:
console.log(x); // undefined
var x = 5;
â¡ JS internally interprets as:
var x;
console.log(x); // undefined
x = 5;
ğŸ§  Example 2 â€“ let and const (Temporal Dead Zone):
console.log(a); // âŒ ReferenceError
let a = 10;
let and const are hoisted, but not initialized. Accessing them before declaration gives a ReferenceError.

ğŸ§  Example 3 â€“ Function Declaration:
greet(); // âœ… Works
function greet() {
  console.log("Hello!");
}
âœ… Function declarations are fully hoisted.

ğŸ§  Example 4 â€“ Function Expression (not hoisted):
greet(); // âŒ TypeError
var greet = function() {
  console.log("Hi");
};
Only the var greet part is hoisted, not the function definition.

ğŸ§¾ In short:
Hoisting is when variable and function declarations are moved to the top of their scope before code execution.
var is hoisted as undefined, let/const go into Temporal Dead Zone, and function declarations are fully hoisted.

